04207nam a22005775i 9780226559223DE-B159720191022022751.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191022s2018    ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802265592237 a10.7208/97802265592232doi  a(DE-B1597)524979  a(OCoLC)1061503031  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aPR3014b.E48 2018eb 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a822.3/32231 aElden, Stuart, eauthor.10aShakespearean Territories /cStuart Elden. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2018  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Shakespearean Territories -- t1. Divided Territory: The Geo-politics of King Lear -- t2. Vulnerable Territories: Regional Geopolitics in Hamlet and Macbeth -- t3. The Territories: Majesty and Possession in King John -- t4. Economic Territories: Laws, Economies, Agriculture, and Banishment in Richard II -- t5. Legal Territories: Conquest and Contest in Henry V and Edward III -- t6. Colonial Territories: From The Tempest to the Eastern Mediterranean -- t7. Measuring Territories: The Techniques of Rule -- t8. Corporeal Territories: The Political Bodies of Coriolanus -- t9. Outside Territory: The Forest in Titus Andronicus and As You Like It -- tCoda: Beyond Pale Territories -- tReferences to Shakespeare's Plays -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aShakespeare was an astute observer of contemporary life, culture, and politics. The emerging practice of territory as a political concept and technology did not elude his attention. In Shakespearean Territories, Stuart Elden reveals just how much Shakespeare's unique historical position and political understanding can teach us about territory. Shakespeare dramatized a world of technological advances in measuring, navigation, cartography, and surveying, and his plays open up important ways of thinking about strategy, economy, the law, and colonialism, providing critical insight into a significant juncture in history. Shakespeare's plays explore many territorial themes: from the division of the kingdom in King Lear, to the relations among Denmark, Norway, and Poland in Hamlet,  to questions of disputed land and the politics of banishment in Richard II. Elden traces how Shakespeare developed a nuanced understanding of the complicated concept and practice of territory and, more broadly, the political-geographical relations between people, power, and place. A meticulously researched study of over a dozen classic plays, Shakespearean Territories will provide new insights for geographers, political theorists, and Shakespearean scholars alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aEnglish dramay17th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish dramayEarly modern and Elizabethan, 1500-1600xHistory and criticism. 0aGeography in literature. 0aGeopolitics in literature. 4aBoundaries. 4aGeography. 4aPolitics. 4aSpace. 4aTerritory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226559223423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226559223.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles